<table width="100%" style="margin-top:10px">
<tr>
	<td>
		<h2>SPOJ Problem Set (classical)</h2>
				<h1>23492. One piece</h1>
		<h2>Problem code: QTDIVIDE</h2>
	</td>
	</tr>
</table>

<p align="justify">
<p>One of DB and TN common interests is traveling. One day, they went to Grand Line and found One Piece !</p>
<p>The One Piece treasure has n gold coins (n is even). Both them like gold coins, but they evaluate them as different values. So they decided to divide those coins by following method :</p>
<p>DB and TN do n / 2 steps, at each step, DB choose 2 coins, TN takes the coin that she evaluates it greater, and DB take the rest coin.</p>
<p>Let&rsquo;s help DB find how to take the maximum value at possible.</p>
<h3>Input</h3>
<pre><p>First line : a single integer n (n is even) &ndash; the number of coins</p></pre>
<pre><p>Second line : n integers a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, &hellip;, a<sub>n. </sub>a<sub>i</sub> is the value of i<sup>th</sup> coin that TN evaluates.</p></pre>
<pre><p>Third line : n integers b<sub>1</sub>, b<sub>2</sub>, &hellip;, b<sub>n. </sub>b<sub>i</sub> is the value of i<sup>th</sup> coin that DB evaluates.</p></pre>
<h3>Output</h3>
<pre><p>First line : an integer S &ndash; the maximum value DB can take.</p></pre>
<pre><p>
Last n / 2 lines : i<sup>th</sup> line contains two number x and y (1 &le; x, y &le; n), are the indexes of two <br />coins that DB choose on i<sup>th</sup> step. Each coin must be chose exact one time.
</p></pre>
<pre><p>If there are multiple ways, just print any of them.</p></pre>
<h3>Constraints</h3>
<pre><p>2 &le; n &le; 500 000</p>
<p>1 &le; a<sub>i</sub> &le; 10<sup>9</sup></p>
<p>1 &le; b<sub>i</sub> &le; 10<sup>9</sup></p>
<p>Note that a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, &hellip;, a<sub>n</sub> are n distinct integers.</p></pre>
<h3>Example</h3>
<pre><strong>Input:</strong>
&nbsp;
6
6 10 11 18 5 14
1 7 6 12 15 1
</pre>
<pre><strong>Output:</strong>
&nbsp;
28
5 1
2 6
3 4
</pre>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Warning: large Input/Output data, be careful with certain languages</strong></p>
<p><strong><br /></strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

